171":"about 1171","18 Dec 1896":"18 December 1896","15 Dec 1896":"15 December 1896","1173":"1173","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1248":"1248","1146":"1146","ABT 1200":"about 1200","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1144":"1144","Oxburgh Hall, Oxborough, Norfolk, England":"Oxborough, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Oxburg, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tudenham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Tuddenham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tuddenham","meanings":["English: locative name, principally from from East or West Tuddenham (Norfolk), but also from Tuddenham (Suffolk) or Tuddenham Saint Martin (Suffolk)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John I Tudenham was born about 1171, in Oxborough, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de Tudenham, was 29 and his mother, Maud Glanville, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Tudenham."},"et":{"about 1171–":"umbes 1171–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1171–Male":"1171–Surnud","1173–1173":"1173–1173","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1200–1248":"1200–1248","1144–1210":"1144–1210","1146–1173":"1146–1173","about 1170":"umbes 1170","about 1171":"umbes 1171","18 Dec 1896":"18. detsember 1896","15 Dec 1896":"15. detsember 1896","1173":"1173","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1248":"1248","1146":"1146","ABT 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1144":"1144","Oxburgh Hall, Oxborough, Norfolk, England":"Oxborough, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Oxburg, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1171–":"noin 1171–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1171–Male":"1171–Kuollut","1173–1173":"1173–1173","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1200–1248":"1200–1248","1144–1210":"1144–1210","1146–1173":"1146–1173","about 1170":"noin 1170","about 1171":"noin 1171","18 Dec 1896":"18. joulukuuta 1896","15 Dec 1896":"15. joulukuuta 1896","1173":"1173","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1248":"1248","1146":"1146","ABT 1200":"noin 1200","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1144":"1144","Oxburgh Hall, Oxborough, Norfolk, England":"Oxborough, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Oxburg, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1171–":"environ 1171–Décé